  <discussion>Lorentziella imbricata is known from Bastrop, Brazos, Burnet, Cameron, Gillespie, Llano, and Travis counties in central Texas.  It is named for the closely imbricate distal leaves.  In Texas, fertilization and sporophyte growth occur in the winter months and by late spring little trace of the above-ground plants remain.  Spores have been described as angular, probably due to packing and space constraints within the capsule.  Stomata have been described as having a single guard cell with a central opening or two guard cells.  Careful study of guard cells reveals that most are single-celled, 2-nucleate with a central opening.</discussion>
